    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but if the \"catastrophic failure\" of stability was so obvious, doesn't that make the whole decision to intervene fundamentally wrong? it feels like we're just saying \"the goal was good but the result was bad\" to avoid admitting that interventionism itself is a flawed doctrine that just creates more problems than it solves. shouldn't we just accept that these kinds of operations are almost always a mistake?",
